The grasshopper years of Latin America
The bad news continues to accumulate these days in Latin America.
Economic conditions are deteriorating almost everywhere, social cohesion is fraying, and political instability is growing.
This is hardly surprising since most countries in Latin America have spent the last twenty years going nowhere.
Capitals have been sold and national debts have been excessively increased, but nothing lasting and beneficial has been achieved.
These years have really been eaten by the grasshoppers.
Over the past 20 years, the annual GDP growth per capita in Latin America reached an average of 0.35%.
At this rate, an economy would take 200 years to double.
The standard of living doubles every decade in Asia.
With such anaemic growth, how can Latin America hope to compete in the global market except through timid increases in wages?
The economic stagnation is the result of bad government, not bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may start to resemble Africa - a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors have placed it on this path.
Firstly, in the rush for privatization, everything, from public services to manufacturing industries, has been sold at auction.
For a brief moment, the sale of capital helped to balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, revenues derived from privatization have produced little in the context of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the liquidation of state assets was accompanied by a massive foreign loan.
In some cases, particularly in Argentina, the loan made by national buyers has exhausted all available credit ranges.
Other countries have not fallen to the level of Argentina, but solvability is a problem in almost all Latin American countries.
Secondly, since the reform has not brought prosperity, the region has become disheartened.
The influx of capital has produced a wealth effect, but only as long as they existed.
When the money stopped flowing, the wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would engage in another decade of structural reforms that would test the patience of ordinary Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without more deep reforms, too few preconditions for economic growth will be met to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma announces the third factor: incompetent policies.
The governments that functioned along technocratic lines and considered economic growth as a rising tide that lifts all the boats have disappeared.
Unskilled presidents succeed each other in Argentina.
Institutions are being put to the ground, property rights are being questioned and a random and even more corrupt redistribution effort is underway.
The Peru and Venezuela have hardly better chances; Brazil can soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacia da Silva and his team, which are leading the opinion polls in the period preceding the Brazilian presidential elections, indicates that a large part of the Latin American population is prepared to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from prevailing economic thought and politics that capital has already begun to flee - even if the elections are only a few months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but this may well prove ephemeral.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance continues to deteriorate, the economy risks a hard landing.
As for all the good news about the emerging democracy of Mexico, its president is starting to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what it should be doing.
The fourth factor concerns the desperately low savings rate that is endemic to the Americas.
Indeed, this is the result of financial economics because where there is little savings, there is little investment - and little base to accumulate capital and increase productivity.
The Venezuela now sighs for the fat years of the 1970 OPEC - to which it did not participate, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
The wealth of Argentina is now taking a vacation in Miami, perhaps for good.
Brazil and Mexico serve as perfect examples of countries that have sold their assets and borrowed rather than saved.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where the savings and investment rates reach almost 40%, where the current account is in surplus and where there is no public debt.
The government institutions are in favor of the market and the population is well-educated, disciplined and flexible in their learning.
The rewards for taking risks and initiative are immediate and strongly motivating.
You cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
Its per capita GDP represents only half that of Brazil.
But with growth in China's coastal region at about 15% per year, can it seriously be doubted that in the next 15 years, it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the enormous problems encountered, things continue to go well, first of all due to the massive inflow of foreign direct investment and the imminent benefits of accession to the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to fall apart: governments are backtracking on reforms and the economy is losing ground to the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds were pouring in, but those times are largely over.
We must therefore expect much worse economic, social and political news in the years to come.
The demagogues such as Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem -- an Argentine presidential candidate once again -- may seem like a bad joke, but whoever is concerned about the fate of Latin America should not laugh.
